#let images = (
  "23.1": (
    caption: [The coupling of energy-releasing and energy-requiring chemical transformations is the basis of energy flow in ecosystems. Energy is transferred from the reactants in an energy-releasing oxidation to the products of an energy-requiring reduction.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-33-45.png"
  ),
  "23.2": (
    caption: [Biochemical transformations may be linked together in biochemical pathways. As energy flows through an ecosystem, elements alternate between assimilatory and dissimilatory transformations.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-34-15.png"
  ),
  "23.3": (
    caption: [The cycling of elements through ecosystems may be modeled as a set of compartments. Within each compartment, subcompartments can be recognized, such as autotrophs, animals, detritus, and microbes for available organic forms.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-34-36.png"
  ),
  "23.4": (
    caption: [The global hydrologic cycle is analogous to the cycles of chemical elements. Estimated sizes of compartments and transfers are expressed in teratons (tt) and tt per year, respectively.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-35-12.png"
  ),
  "23.5": (
    caption: [The global carbon cycle involves diverse biochemical and chemical transformations. Estimated sizes of compartments and transfers are expressed in gigatons (Gt) and Gt per year, respectively.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-35-31.png"
  ),
  "23.6": (
    caption: [Carbon cycles between organic and inorganic forms. Methane is produced only by certain archaebacteria under anaerobic conditions.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-35-57.png"
  ),
  "23.7": (
    caption: [Most of the earth’s carbon is locked up in sedimentary rocks. Limestone deposits represent calcium carbonate precipitated out of solution in ancient shallow seas.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-36-33.png"
  ),
  "23.8": (
    caption: [The “skeletons” of coralline algae are made of calcium carbonate, precipitated in conjunction with their uptake of dissolved carbon dioxide during photosynthesis.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-36-59.png"
  ),
  "23.9": (
    caption: [Concentrations of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere have decreased since the early Paleozoic era. Values are expressed in multiples of the concentration at the beginning of the Industrial Revolution.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-37-17.png"
  ),
  "23.10": (
    caption: [Fossil soils reveal changes in the biosphere. Changes in paleosols during the middle Paleozoic era show increases in terrestrial vegetation and progressive weathering of soils, leading to sequestration of atmospheric carbon dioxide in coal and carbonate sediments.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-38-38.png"
  ),
  "23.11": (
    caption: [Nitrogen assumes several different oxidation states as it cycles through ecosystems. Estimated sizes of compartments and transfers are expressed in gigatons (Gt) and Gt per year, respectively.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-39-25.png"
  ),
  "23.12": (
    caption: [Some plants provide anaerobic environments for nitrogen-fixing bacteria. (a) Nodules on the roots of legumes harbor symbiotic nitrogen-fixing Rhizobium bacteria. (b) Numerous brown rods in the micrograph are Rhizobium bacteria within a symbiosome.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-39-48.png"
  ),
  "23.13": (
    caption: [Nitrogen from nitrate in precipitation is quickly immobilized by bacteria and in organic matter in forest soil. The gradual disappearance of the stable isotope 15N reflects uptake by plants as nitrogen is released by decomposition.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-40-14.png"
  ),
  "23.14": (
    caption: [The phosphorus cycle has fewer steps than other element cycles. Estimated sizes of compartments and transfers are expressed in gigatons (Gt) and Gt per year, respectively.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-40-42.png"
  ),
  "23.15": (
    caption: [The cycling pathways of carbon and phosphorus differ in temperate lakes. (a) Phytoplankton obtain carbon as dissolved CO2, which is abundant in summer. (b) Phosphorus comes from organic detritus, which is depleted by late summer.],
    path: "../fig/fig-2025-10-22-13-41-11.png"
  ),
